{"title_page": "Devil's Food", "text_new": "{{about||the cake|Devil's food cake|the Alice Cooper song|Welcome to My Nightmare}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Devil's Food\n| type       = Compilation album\n| artist     = [[Supersuckers]]\n| cover      = Devilsfood.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 5, 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62456/supersuckers-go-with-the-marketing-flow|title=Supersuckers Go With The Marketing Flow|date=June 29, 2005|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock and roll]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Mid-Fi]] Recordings\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Live at the Tractor Tavern]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/devils-food-a-collection-of-rare-treats-evil-sweets!-mw0000460977|title=Devil's Food: A Collection of Rare Treats & Evil Sweets! - Supersuckers &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Devil's Food''''' is a singles compilation by the [[United States|American]] [[rock and roll]] [[rock band|band]] [[Supersuckers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattleweekly.com/music/the-songs-dont-all-sound-the-same/|title=The Songs Don't All Sound the Same|first=Michaelangelo|last=Matos|date=October 9, 2006|website=Seattle Weekly}}</ref> It was released in April 2005 on [[Mid-Fi]] records.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Gato Negro\"\n#\"Shake It Off\"\n#\"[[Hey Ya!|Hey Ya]]\"\n#\"Teenage Shutdown\" \n#\"Doublewide\" <small>(country version)</small>\n#\"Team Man\"\t\n#\"Can Pipe\"\n#\"[[Rubber Biscuit]]\"\n#\"Born with a Tail\" <small>(country version)</small> \t\n#\"Devil's Food\"\n#\"Sail On\"\n#\"Kid's Got It Comin'\"\n#\"Eastbound & Down\"\n#\"Then I'm Gone\"\n#\"Flyin' Into the Mid-Day Sun\"\n#\"End of an Era\"\n\n==Notes==\n*\"Gato Negro\" originally appeared on a split single with the band [[Zeke (band)|Zeke]].\n*\"Hey Ya\" is a cover of the song by [[OutKast]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotimes.com/HeadCheese/archives/2005/04/27/head-cheese|title=Head cheese|first=Metro Times music|last=staff|website=Detroit Metro Times}}</ref>\n*\"Teenage Shutdown\" is a cover of the song by [[Electric Frankenstein]], originally appearing on ''[[Splitsville 1]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/supersuckerselectric_frankenstein-splitsville_vol|title=Supersuckers/Electric Frankenstein Splitsville Vol. 1|website=exclaim.ca}}</ref>\n*\"Rubber Biscuit\" is a cover of the song by [[The Chips]].\n*\"Sail On\" is a cover of the song by [[The Commodores]].\n*\"Eastbound & Down\" is a cover of the [[Jerry Reed]] song \"[[East Bound and Down]]\" originally written for the movie ''[[Smokey and the Bandit]]''.\n*\"Doublewide\" and \"Born With a Tail\" are country versions of songs originally appearing on the band's 1995 [[Sub Pop]] album, ''[[The Sacrilicious Sounds of the Supersuckers]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2000s-punk-rock-album-stub}}\n\n{{Supersuckers}}\n\n[[Category:Supersuckers albums]]\n[[Category:2005 compilation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the cake|[[Devil's food cake]]|the Alice Cooper song|[[Welcome to My Nightmare]]}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Devil's Food\n| type       = Compilation album\n| artist     = [[Supersuckers]]\n| cover      = Devilsfood.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 5, 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62456/supersuckers-go-with-the-marketing-flow|title=Supersuckers Go With The Marketing Flow|date=June 29, 2005|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock and roll]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Mid-Fi]] Recordings\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Live at the Tractor Tavern]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/devils-food-a-collection-of-rare-treats-evil-sweets!-mw0000460977|title=Devil's Food: A Collection of Rare Treats & Evil Sweets! - Supersuckers &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Devil's Food''''' is a singles compilation by the [[United States|American]] [[rock and roll]] [[rock band|band]] [[Supersuckers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattleweekly.com/music/the-songs-dont-all-sound-the-same/|title=The Songs Don't All Sound the Same|first=Michaelangelo|last=Matos|date=October 9, 2006|website=Seattle Weekly}}</ref> It was released in April 2005 on [[Mid-Fi]] records.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Gato Negro\"\n#\"Shake It Off\"\n#\"[[Hey Ya!|Hey Ya]]\"\n#\"Teenage Shutdown\" \n#\"Doublewide\" <small>(country version)</small>\n#\"Team Man\"\t\n#\"Can Pipe\"\n#\"[[Rubber Biscuit]]\"\n#\"Born with a Tail\" <small>(country version)</small> \t\n#\"Devil's Food\"\n#\"Sail On\"\n#\"Kid's Got It Comin'\"\n#\"Eastbound & Down\"\n#\"Then I'm Gone\"\n#\"Flyin' Into the Mid-Day Sun\"\n#\"End of an Era\"\n\n==Notes==\n*\"Gato Negro\" originally appeared on a split single with the band [[Zeke (band)|Zeke]].\n*\"Hey Ya\" is a cover of the song by [[OutKast]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotimes.com/HeadCheese/archives/2005/04/27/head-cheese|title=Head cheese|first=Metro Times music|last=staff|website=Detroit Metro Times}}</ref>\n*\"Teenage Shutdown\" is a cover of the song by [[Electric Frankenstein]], originally appearing on ''[[Splitsville 1]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/supersuckerselectric_frankenstein-splitsville_vol|title=Supersuckers/Electric Frankenstein Splitsville Vol. 1|website=exclaim.ca}}</ref>\n*\"Rubber Biscuit\" is a cover of the song by [[The Chips]].\n*\"Sail On\" is a cover of the song by [[The Commodores]].\n*\"Eastbound & Down\" is a cover of the [[Jerry Reed]] song \"[[East Bound and Down]]\" originally written for the movie ''[[Smokey and the Bandit]]''.\n*\"Doublewide\" and \"Born With a Tail\" are country versions of songs originally appearing on the band's 1995 [[Sub Pop]] album, ''[[The Sacrilicious Sounds of the Supersuckers]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2000s-punk-rock-album-stub}}\n\n{{Supersuckers}}\n\n[[Category:Supersuckers albums]]\n[[Category:2005 compilation albums]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devil%27s_Food"}
{"title_page": "Designated survivor", "text_new": "{{short description|An individual in the presidential line of succession}}\n{{About|the U.S. contingency plan to safeguard its line of presidential succession|the 2016 TV series|Designated Survivor (TV series)}}\n\nIn the United States, a '''designated survivor''' (or '''designated successor''') is a named individual in the [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[United States presidential line of succession|line of succession]], chosen to stay (at a secure and undisclosed location) away from events such as [[State of the Union]] addresses and [[United States presidential inauguration|presidential inaugurations]]. The practice of [[Designation (law)|designating a successor]] is intended to safeguard [[Continuity of government|continuity in the office of the president]] in the event the president along with the vice president and multiple other officials in the presidential line of succession died in a [[mass-casualty incident]]. The procedure originated in the 1950s during the [[Cold War]] with its risk of [[nuclear attack]].\n\nIf such an event occurred, the surviving official highest in the line of succession as delineated in the [[Presidential Succession Act of 1947]] would become [[acting president of the United States]]. Consequently, the individual named must be [[President of the United States#Eligibility|eligible to serve as president]]. In practice, the designated survivor is usually a member of the president's [[Cabinet of the United States|Cabinet]], and is chosen by the president.\n\n==Selection==\nThe process for selection of the designated survivor has been described by those involved to be entirely random. However, the character of the event for which a designated survivor is being selected may cause some officials to be avoided in the selection process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/how-is-the-designated-survivor-chosen-rick-perry-wont-be-at-the-2019-sotu-15913072|title=How Is The Designated Survivor Chosen? Rick Perry Won\u2019t Be At The 2019 SOTU|author=Seth Millstein|date=6 February 2019|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|quote=CBS News reports that the president and their staff are responsible for selecting the designated survivor, and [[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]], Barack Obama's former lead speechwriter, spoke to The Ringer about the designated survivor selection process in 2016. Favreau initially said that the process is \"entirely random,\" but then backtracked a bit and said that sometimes, the designated survivor depends on what the president intends to say in their speech.}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=government source needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==List of designated survivors==\n{{incomplete list|date=April 2017}}\n{{for|a list of designated survivors in popular culture|United States presidential line of succession in fiction}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! data-sort-type=\"usLongDate\" | Date !! Occasion !! Designee !! Position !! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| February 18, 1981 || Presidential Address to Joint Session of Congress<ref name=\"incoming\">1981, 1989, 1993, 2001, 2009 and 2017 speeches were given by incoming Presidents and not formal \"State of the Union\" addresses.</ref> || [[Terrel Bell]] || [[United States Secretary of Education|Secretary of Education]] || <ref name=bewitched>{{cite news|last=Hershey, Jr.|first=Robert D.|title=State of Union: Bewitched by Pageant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/27/us/washington-talk-presidential-message-state-of-union-bewitched-by-pageant.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 January 1988}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 25, 1984 || [[1984 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Samuel Pierce]] || [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] || <ref name=sou>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/sou_cabinet.php|title=Cabinet Members Who Did Not Attend the State of the Union Address|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu}}</ref><ref name=\"Senate\">{{cite web | url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/resources/pdf/StateUnionCabinet.pdf | title=Cabinet members who did not attend the State of the Union Address (since 1984) | publisher=[[United States Senate Historical Office]]}}</ref><ref>1984: UPI, \"Washington Dateline.\" Jan 25, 1984</ref><ref name=\"sotu2013\" />\n|-\n| January 21, 1985 || [[Second inauguration of Ronald Reagan|Presidential Inauguration]] || [[Margaret Heckler]] || [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary of Health and Human Services]] || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zKMRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qukDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3600,1975112|title=Gainesville Sun - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 6, 1985 || [[1985 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Howard M. Baldrige, Jr.|Malcolm Baldrige]] || [[United States Secretary of Commerce|Secretary of Commerce]] || <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref>1985: UPI, \"Washington News.\" Feb 6, 1985</ref>\n|-\n| February 4, 1986 || [[1986 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[John Rusling Block|John Block]] || [[United States Secretary of Agriculture|Secretary of Agriculture]] || <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref>1986: UPI, \"Washington News.\" Feb 4, 1986</ref>\n|-\n| January 27, 1987 || [[1987 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Richard Edmund Lyng|Richard Lyng]] || [[United States Secretary of Agriculture|Secretary of Agriculture]] || <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref>1987: UPI, \"Washington News.\" Jan 28, 1987</ref>\n|-\n| January 25, 1988 || [[1988 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Donald Hodel]] || [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] || <ref name