nal/designated-survivor-prepares-for-inauguration-day|title=Designated survivor prepares|date=2017-01-19|website=WGBA|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | February 2, 2005 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[2005 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Donald Evans]] || [[United States Secretary of Commerce|Secretary of Commerce]] || rowspan=\"2\" | <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref name=\"protempore\">For the 2005, 2006 and 2007 State of the Union addresses, the President pro tempore of the Senate would have been the highest-ranking survivor.</ref><ref>2005: The New York Times, \"Five Officials Skip State of the Union Address.\" Feb 2, 2005.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ted Stevens]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Alaska|AK]]) || [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore of the Senate]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | January 31, 2006 || rowspan=2 | [[2006 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Jim Nicholson (Secretary of Veterans Affairs)|Jim Nicholson]] || [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]] || rowspan=2 | <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref name=\"protempore\" /><ref>2006: ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', \"A Message of Energy, Strength.\" Feb 1, 2006.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ted Stevens]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Alaska|AK]]) || [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore of the Senate]]\n|-\n| January 23, 2007 || [[2007 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Alberto Gonzales]] || [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] || <ref name=sou/><ref name=\"Senate\" /><ref name=\"sotu2013\" /><ref name=\"protempore\" /><ref>2007: Washington Post, \"The Reliable Source.\" Page C3. Jan 25, 2007.</ref>\n|-\n| January 28, 2008 || [[2008 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]] || [[Dirk Kempthorne]] || [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Sec