-joint-session-of-congress-on-feb-28/|title=Trump to address a joint session of Congress on Feb. 28|first1=Mike|last1=DeBonis|first2=Jenna|last2=Johnson|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2017-01-24|accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/PhilipRucker/status/836758579998765057|title=Philip Rucker on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2017-02-28|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/va-secretary-david-shulkin-chosen-designated-survivor/story?id=45815247|title=VA Secretary David Shulkin chosen as designated survivor|work=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|January 30, 2018\n|[[2018 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]]\n|[[Sonny Perdue]]\n|[[United States Secretary of Agriculture|Secretary of Agriculture]]\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/agriculture-secretary-sonny-perdue-is-designated-survivor-for-this-years-state-of-the-union-address/article/2647568|title=Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue State of the Union 'designated survivor'|last=Westwood|first=Sarah|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 5, 2019\n|[[2019 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]]\n|[[Rick Perry]]\n|[[United States Secretary of Energy|Secretary of Energy]]\n|<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/05/politics/rick-perry-designated-survivor/index.html|title = Energy Secretary Rick Perry is the designated survivor|last = Klein|first = Betsy|last2 = Gray|first2 = Noah|date = February 5, 2019|accessdate = February 5, 2019|work = [[CNN]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 4, 2020\n|[[2020 State of the Union Address|State of the Union]]\n|[[David Bernhardt]]\n|[[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]]\n|<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/04/david-bernhardt-sotu-designated-survivor-110786|title = The State of the Union\u2019s designated survivor: Interior Secretary David Bernhardt|last = Choi|first = Matthew|date = February 4, 2020|accessdate = February 4, 2020|work = [[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/state-of-the-union-designated-survivor-interior-secretary-david-bernhardt-2020-02-04/|title=What to know about the \"designated survivor\" and State of the Union|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/resources/pdf/StateUnionCabinet.pdf U.S. Senate's list of cabinet members who did not attend the State of the Union Address (since 1984)]\n* [http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/sou_cabinet.php Cabinet Members Who Did Not Attend the State of the Union Address Reagan (1984) \u2013 Trump] The American Presidency Project [online]. Gerhard Peters (database). Santa Barbara, California: University of California (hosted).\n\n{{Potuslists}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Designated Survivor}}\n[[Category:United States presidential succession]]\n[[Category:Disaster preparedness in the United States]]\n[[Category:Continuity of government in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|An individual in the presidential line of succession}}\n{{About|the U.S. contingency plan to safeguard its line of presidential succession|the 2016 TV series|Designated Survivor (TV series)}}\n\nIn the United States, a '''designated survivor''' (or '''designated successor''') is a named individual in the [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[United States presidential line of succession|line of succession]], chosen to stay (at a secure and undisclosed location) away from events such as [[State of the Union]] addresses and [[United States presidential inauguration|presidential inaugurations]]. The practice of [[Designation (law)|designating a successor]] is intended to safeguard [[Continuity of government|continuity in the office of the president]] in the event the president along with the vice president and multiple other officials in the presidential line of succession died in a [[mass-casualty incident]]. The procedure originated in the 1950s during the [[Cold War]] with its risk of [[nuclear attack]].\n\nIf such an event occurred, the surviving official highest in the line of succession as delineated in the [[Presidential Succession Act of 1947]] would become [[acting president of the United States]]. Consequently, the individual named must be [[President of the United States#Eligibility|eligible to serve as president]]. In practice, the designated survivor is usually a member of the president's [[Cabinet of the United States|Cabinet]], and is chosen by the president.\n\n==Selection==\nThe process for selection of the designated survivor has been described by those involved to be entirely random. However, the character of the event for which a designated survivor is being selected may cause some officials to be avoided in the selection process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/how-is-the-designated-survivor-chosen-rick-perry-wont-be-at-the-2019-sotu-15913072|title=How Is The Designated Survivor Chosen? Rick Perry Won\u2019t Be At The 2019 SOTU|author=Seth Millstein|date=6 February 2019|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|quote=CBS News reports that the president and their staff are responsible for selecting the designated survivor, and [[Jon Favreau (speechwriter)|Jon Favreau]], Barack Obama's former lead speechwriter, spoke to The Ringer about the designated survivor selection process in 2016. Favreau initially said that the process is \"entirely random,\" but then backtracked a bit and said that sometimes, the designated survivor depends on what the president intends to say in their speech.}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=government source needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==List of designated survivors==\n{{incomplete list|date=April 2017}}\n{{For2|a list of designated survivors in popular culture|[[United States presidential line of succession in fiction]]}}\n\n{|clas