{"title_page": "Cloth facemask", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|A mask made of common textiles worn over the mouth and nose}}[[File:HomemadeFacemask.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Homemade cloth face mask]]\nA '''cloth facemask''' is a mask made of common [[Textile|textiles]], usually [[cotton]], worn over the mouth and nose.  Unlike [[Surgical mask|surgical masks]] and [[Respirator|respirators]] such as [[N95 mask|N95 masks]], they are not subject to regulation, and there is currently little research or guidance on their effectiveness as a protective measure against [[Transmission (medicine)|infectious disease transmission]] or [[Particulates|particulate]] [[air pollution]].\n\nThey were routinely used by healthcare workers starting from the late 19th century until the mid 20th century.  In the 1960s they fell out of use in the [[Developed country|developed world]] in favor of modern surgical masks, but their use has persisted in [[Developing country|developing countries]].  During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], their use in developed countries was revived as a last resort [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|due to shortages]] of surgical masks and respirators.\n\n== Usage ==\n[[File:Use of Cloth Face Coverings to Help Slow the Spread of COVID-19.pdf|thumb|Guidance from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] on using and making cloth masks during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<ref name=\":5\" />]]\nReusable cloth facemasks are predominantly used in developing countries and especially in Asia.  They contrast with [[Surgical mask|surgical masks]] and [[Respirator|respirators]] such as [[N95 mask|N95 masks]], which are made of [[nonwoven fabric]] formed through a [[melt blowing]] process, and are regulated for their effectiveness.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.nap.edu/catalog/11637|title=Reusability of Facemasks During an Influenza Pandemic: Facing the Flu|date=July 24, 2006|publisher=National Academies Press|year=|isbn=978-0-309-10182-0|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=6, 36\u201338|doi=10.17226/11637}}</ref>  Like surgical masks, and unlike respirators, cloth facemasks do not provide a seal around the face.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn healthcare settings, they are used on sick patients as \"source control\" to reduce disease transmission through [[Respiratory droplet|respiratory droplets]], and by healthcare workers when surgical masks and respirators are unavailable.  Cloth facemasks are generally recommended for use only as a last resort if supplies of surgical masks and respirators are exhausted.<ref name=\":0\" />   They are also used by the general pubic in household and community settings as perceived protection against both infectious diseases and [[Particulates|particulate]] [[air pollution]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=MacIntyre|first=C. R.|last2=Chughtai|first2=A. A.|date=April 9, 2015|title=Facemasks for the prevention of infection in healthcare and community settings|url=http://akkie.mods.jp/2019-nCoV/images/c/c0/%E3%82%B5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B8%E3%82%AB%E3%83%AB%E3%83%9E%E3%82%B9%E3%82%AF%E5%8C%BB%E7%99%82vs%E5%B8%82%E4%B8%AD%E6%84%9F%E6%9F%93%E4%BA%88%E9%98%B2%EF%BC%9A%E7%B7%8F%E8%AA%AC_%282015%2C_MacIntyre%29.pdf|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=350|issue=apr09 1|pages=h694\u2013h694|doi=10.1136/bmj.h694|issn=1756-1833|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Shakya|first=Kabindra M.|last2=Noyes|first2=Alyssa|last3=Kallin|first3=Randa|last4=Peltier|first4=Richard E.|date=May 1, 2017|title=Evaluating the efficacy of cloth facemasks in reducing particulate matter exposure|url=https://www.ceh.org.in/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/1-Shakaya-Face-Masks-JESEE-2016.pdf|journal=Journal of Exposure Science & Environmental Epidemiology|language=en|volume=27|issue=3|pages=352\u2013357|doi=10.1038/jes.2016.42|issn=1559-064X|via=}}</ref>\n\nSeveral types of cloth facemasks are available commercially, especially in Asia.<ref name=\":3\" />   Homemade masks can also be improvised using [[Bandana|bandanas]],<ref name=\":5\" /> [[T-shirt|T-shirts]],<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Handkerchief|handkerchiefs]],<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Scarf|scarves]],<ref name=\":2\" /> or [[Towel|towels]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Effectiveness ==\nAs of 2015, there had been no [[Randomized controlled trial|randomized clinical trials]] or guidance on the use of reusable cloth facemasks.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Chughtai|first=Abrar Ahmad|last2=Seale|first2=Holly|last3=MacIntyre|first3=Chandini Raina|date=June 19, 2013|title=Use of cloth masks in the practice of infection control \u2013 evidence and policy gaps|url=http://www.ijic.info/article/view/11366|journal=International Journal of Infection Control|volume=9|issue=3|doi=10.3396/IJIC.v9i3.020.13|issn=1996-9783}}</ref>  Most research had been performed in the early 20th century, before disposable surgical masks became prevalent.  One 2010 study found that 40\u201390% of particles penetrated a cloth mask.<ref name=\":0\" />  The performance of cloth facemasks varies greatly with the shape, fit, and type of fabric,<ref name=\":3\" /> as well as the fabric fineness and number of layers.<ref name=\":4\" />  As of 2006, no cloth facemasks had been cleared by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] for use as surgical masks.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:165-WW-269B-11-trolley-l.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:165-WW-269B-11-trolley-l.jpg|alt=|thumb| During the [[1918 flu pandemic]], a streetcar conductor in [[Seattle]] refuses a person who attempts to board without wearing a mask.]]\nThe first recorded use of a cloth facemask involved the French [[surgeon]] [[Paul Berger]] during an 1897 operation in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Lowry\">{{cite journal|last= Lowry|first=H. C.|date= November 1, 1947|title= Some Landmarks in Surgical Technique|url= |journal= The Ulster Medical Journal|volume= 16|issue= 2|pages= 102\u201313|pmc= 2479244|pmid= 18898288|via=}}</ref> Masks came into use to protect against infectious diseases in the early 20th century.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> A design by [[Lien-teh Wu]], who worked for the Chinese Imperial Court in the fall of 1910 during a [[bubonic plague]] outbreak, was the first that protected users from bacteria in empirical testing; it inspired masks used during the [[1918 flu pandemic]].<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.fastcompany.com/90479846/the-untold-origin-story-of-the-n95-mask|title= The untold origin story of the N95 mask|last= Wilson|first= Mark|date= March 24, 2020|website= Fast Company|language= en-US|access-date= March 27, 2020}}</ref> The first study of mask use by healthcare workers took place in 1918.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" />  In the 1940s, facemasks made from [[cheesecloth]] were used to protect nurses from [[tuberculosis]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last= McNett|first= Esta H.|date= January 1, 1949|title= The Face Mask in Tuberculosis: How the cheese-cloth face mask has been developed as a protective agent in tuberculosis |url=https://journals.lww.com/ajnonline/Citation/1949/01000/The_Face_Mask_in_Tuberculosis__How_the.30.aspx |journal= AJN The American Journal of Nursing |volume= 49|issue= 1|pages= 32\u201336|issn=0002-936X|via=}}</ref>\n\nCloth masks were largely supplanted by modern [[Surgical mask|surgical masks]] made of [[nonwoven fabric]] in the 1960s,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> although their use continued in developing countries.<ref name=\":0\" />  They were used in Asia during the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], and in West Africa during the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|2013\u20132016 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) in March 2020 recommended that if neither respirators nor surgical masks are available, as a last resort, it may be necessary for healthcare workers to use masks that have never been evaluated or approved by NIOSH or homemade masks, though caution should be exercised when considering this option.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/respirators-strategy/crisis-alternate-strategies.html|title=Strategies for Optimizing the Supply of N95 Respirators: Crisis/Alternate Strategies|last=|first=|date=March 17, 2020|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}} {{PD-inline}}</ref>  In April 2020, CDC recommended that the general public wear cloth face coverings in public settings where other [[social distancing]] measures are difficult to maintain such as, grocery stores and pharmacies, especially in areas of significant community-based transmission, due to the significance of [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]] and pre-symptomatic disease transmission.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/diy-cloth-face-coverings.html|title=Use of Cloth Face Coverings to Help Slow the Spread of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=April 4, 2020|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}} {{PD-inline}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/cloth-face-cover.html|title=Recommendation Regarding the Use of Cloth Face Coverings, Especially in Areas of Significant Community-Based Transmission|last=|first=|date=April 3, 2020|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) advice to the public in the context of [[COVID-19]] endorsed the use of masks only under certain conditions:<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url= https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/when-and-how-to-use-masks\n |title= Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: When and how to use masks\n |year= 2020\n |website= World Health Organization\n |publisher= World Health Organization\n |access-date= April 6, 2020\n }}\n</ref>\n<blockquote>\n* If you are healthy, you only need to wear a mask if you are taking care of a person with suspected 2019-nCoV infection.\n* Wear a mask if you are coughing or sneezing.\n* Masks are effective only when used in combination with frequent hand-cleaning with alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]] or soap and water.\n* If you wear a mask, then you must know how to use it and dispose of it properly.\n</blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cloth masks]]\n[[Category:Health]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A mask made of common textiles worn over the mouth and nose}}[[File:HomemadeFacemask.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Homemade cloth face mask]]\nA '''cloth facemask''' is a mask made of common [[Textile|textiles]], usually [[cotton]], worn over the mouth and nose.  Unlike [[Surgical mask|surgical masks]] and [[Respirator|respirators]] such as [[N95 mask|N95 masks]], they are not subject to regulation, and there is currently little research or guidance on their effectiveness as a protective measure against [[Transmission (medicine)|infectious disease transmission]] or [[Particulates|particulate]] [[air pollution]].\n\nThey were routinely used by healthcare workers starting from the late 19th century until the mid 20th century.  In the 1960s they fell out of use in the [[Developed country|developed world]] in favor of modern surgical masks, but their use has persisted in [[Developing country|developing countries]].  During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], their use in developed countries was revived as a last resort [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|due to shortages]] of surgical masks and respirators.\n\n== Usage ==\n[[File:Use of Cloth Face Coverings to Help Slow the Spread of COVID-19.pdf|thumb|Guidance from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] on using and making cloth masks during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<ref name=\":5\" />]]\nReusable cloth facemasks are predominantly used in developing countries and especially in Asia.  They contrast with [[Surgical mask|surgical masks]] and [[Respirator|respirators]] such as [[N95 mask|N95 masks]], which are made of [[nonwoven fabric]] formed through a [[melt blowing]] process, and are regulated for their effectiveness.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.nap.edu/catalog/11637|title=Reusability of Facemasks During an Influenza Pandemic: Facing the Flu|date=2006-07-24|publisher=National Academies Press|year=|isbn=978-0-309-10182-0|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=6, 36\u201338|doi=10.17226/11637}}</ref>  Like surgical masks, and unlike respirators, cloth facemasks do not provide a seal around the face.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn healthcare settings, they are used on sick patients as \"source control\" to reduce disease transmission through [[Respiratory droplet|respiratory droplets]], and by healthcare workers when surgical masks and respirators are unavailable.  Cloth facemasks are generally recommended for use only as a last resort if supplies of surgical masks and respirators are exhausted.<ref name=\":0\" />   They are also used by the general pubic in household and community settings as perceived protection against both infectious diseases and [[Particulates|particulate]] [[air pollution]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=MacIntyre|first=C. R.|last2=Chughtai|first2=A. A.|date=2015-04-09|title=Facemasks for the prevention of infection in healthcare and community settings|url=http://akkie.mods.jp/2019-nCoV/images/c/c0/%E3%82%B5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B8%E3%82%AB%E3%83%AB%E3%83%9E%E3%82%B9%E3%82%AF%E5%8C%BB%E7%99%82vs%E5%B8%82%E4%B8%AD%E6%84%