{"title_page": "Probability/Event", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Event_(probability_theory)]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Event_(probability_theory)]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Probability/Event&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Marjorie Rice", "text_new": "{{short description|American amateur mathematician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marjorie Rice\n| image              = [[File:PentagonTilings Rice 2x2.svg|thumb|PentagonTilings Rice 2x2]]\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Four of Rice's pentagon tilings\n| birth_name         = Marjorie Jeuck\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1923|2|16}}\n| birth_place        = St. Petersburg, Florida\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|7|2|1923|2|16}}\n| death_place        = San Diego, California\n| occupation         = amateur mathematician\n| known_for          = Discovery of new tessellating pentagons\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n'''Marjorie Rice''' (n\u00e9e Jeuck)<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/marjorie-rices-secret-pentagons-20170711/|magazine=[[Quanta Magazine]]|title=Marjorie Rice\u2019s Secret Pentagons|first=Natalie|last=Wolchover|date=July 11, 2017}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] amateur mathematician most famous for her discoveries in [[geometry]].<ref name=Doris>[http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm Perplexing Pentagons] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813111016/http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm}}</ref> Rice was born February 16, 1923 in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], and died July 2, 2017 in [[San Diego|San Diego, California]], where she was living with her son and daughter-in-law.\n\n==Geometry==\nMarjorie Rice was a mother of five, who had become an ardent follower of [[Martin Gardner|Martin Gardner\u2019s]] long-running column, \u201cMathematical Games,\u201d which appeared monthly, 1957\u20131986, in the pages of [[Scientific American|Scientific American magazine]]. By the 1970s, Gardner was a popular science writer and amateur mathematician. Rice said later<ref name=\":0\">{{citation|last=Cole|first=K. C.|title=Beating the Pros to the Punch|date=March 11, 1998|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/11/news/mn-27706|journal=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}.</ref> that she would rush to grab each issue from the mail before anyone else could get it, especially her son who subscribed to the magazine.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1975, Rice came across Gardner's articles about [[tessellation]], the mathematics of tiling patterns (determining what kinds of shapes can fit together perfectly without any overlaps or gaps). This is an abstract subject with many scientific applications. In his writings, Gardner claimed that \"only certain types of pentagons could perfectly tile a plane or flat surface, and that all of them were known\u2014or so the mathematicians thought.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Tilings discoveries ===\nDespite having only a high-school education, Rice began devoting her free time to discovering new [[Pentagonal tiling#Monohedral convex pentagonal tilings|pentagonal tiling]]s, ways to tile a [[Plane (geometry)|plane]] (a flat two-dimensional surface) using [[pentagon]]s (a five-sided shape). She worked on the problem in her free time and through the 1975 holiday season \"by drawing diagrams on the kitchen table when no one was around and hiding them when her husband and children came home, or when friends stopped by.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> She even developed her own system of [[Mathematical notation|notation]] to represent the constraints on and relationships between the sides and angles of the pentagons.\n\nIn February 1976, she mailed her discoveries to Gardner using her own home-made notation. He, in turn, sent Rice\u2019s work to [[Doris Schattschneider]], an expert in tiling patterns, who was skeptical at first, saying that Rice\u2019s peculiar notation system seemed odd, like \u201chieroglyphics.\u201d But with careful examination, she was able to validate Rice's results.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBy October 1976, Rice had discovered 58 pentagon tilings (most of them previously unknown), which she arranged into 12 classes. By 1977, she had discovered four new types of tessellating pentagons and over 60 distinct tessellations using pentagons.<ref name=\"Doris\" />\n\nIn the following decade, she discovered several more tiling patterns and three more types of pentagons, thus making major contributions to the field of mathematics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ [[Pentagonal tiling#Monohedral convex pentagonal tilings|Representative tilings]] of four tiling pentagons discovered by Marjorie Rice\n!Type 9\n!Type 11\n!Type 12\n!Type 13\n|- align=center\n|[[File:P5-type9-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type11 chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type12-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type13-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|- align=center\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type9.png|120px]]<BR>b = c = d = e<BR>2A + C = D + 2E = 360\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type11.png|120px]]<BR>2a + c = d = e<BR>A = 90\u00b0, 2B + C = 360\u00b0<BR>C + E = 180\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type12.png|120px]]<BR>2a = d = c + e<BR>A = 90\u00b0, 2B + C = 360\u00b0<BR>C + E = 180\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type13.png|120px]]<BR>d = 2a = 2e<BR>B = E = 90\u00b0, 2A + D = 360\u00b0\n|}\n\n=== Accolades ===\nDoris Schattschneider, who helped Martin Gardner popularize the [[pentagon tiling]] discoveries of Rice,<ref name=\":0\" /> lauded her work as an exciting discovery by an amateur mathematician.<ref>[[Doris Schattschneider]]. \"In praise of amateurs.\" In [[David A. Klarner]], editor, ''The Mathematical Gardner'', pages 140\u2013166. Prindle, Weber & Schmidt, Boston, 1981</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813111016/http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm|title=Perplexing Pentagons|date=2016-08-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, at a regional meeting of the Mathematical Association of America held in [[Los Angeles]], Schattschneider convinced Rice and her husband to attend the presentation of Rice\u2019s work in a lecture. Before concluding her talk, Schattschneider introduced the amateur mathematician who had advanced the study of tessellation. \u201cAnd everybody in the room . . . gave her a standing ovation.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n* One of the tilings discovered by Rice was cut into glazed ceramic tiles, and installed in the foyer of the headquarters of the [[Mathematical Association of America]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conquermaths.com/news/post/index/264/Marjorie-Rice-The-Most-Remarkable-Housewife-You-ve-Never-Heard-Of|title=Marjorie Rice - The Most Remarkable Housewife You've Never Heard Of|access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Her papers and materials in support of her mathematical discoveries are preserved at the Eug\u00e8ne Strens Recreational Mathematics Collection at the [[University of Calgary]] Library, [[Alberta|Alberta, Canada]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/17513472.2017.1399680|title=Marjorie Rice (16 February 1923\u20132 July 2017)|access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of amateur mathematicians]]\n*[[List of Martin Gardner Mathematical Games columns]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://sites.google.com/site/intriguingtessellations/home Marjorie Rice's home page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070820095233/http://tessellations.home.comcast.net/}}\n*[http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/PentagonTilings/ Pentagon Tilings demonstration]\n*Doris Schattschneider. \"In praise of amateurs.\" In David A. Klarner, editor, ''The Mathematical Gardner'', pages 140\u2013166. Prindle, Weber & Schmidt, Boston, 1981\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Marjorie}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Amateur mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Geometers]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:People from St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women mathematicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American amateur mathematician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marjorie Rice\n| image              = [[File:PentagonTilings Rice 2x2.svg|thumb|PentagonTilings Rice 2x2]]\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Rice's pentagon tilings\n| birth_name         = Marjorie Jeuck\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1923|2|16}}\n| birth_place        = St. Petersburg, Florida\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|7|2|1923|2|16}}\n| death_place        = San Diego, California\n| occupation         = amateur mathematician\n| known_for          = Discovery of new tessellating pentagons\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n'''Marjorie Rice''' (n\u00e9e Jeuck)<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/marjorie-rices-secret-pentagons-20170711/|magazine=[[Quanta Magazine]]|title=Marjorie Rice\u2019s Secret Pentagons|first=Natalie|last=Wolchover|date=July 11, 2017}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] amateur mathematician most famous for her discoveries in [[geometry]].<ref name=Doris>[http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm Perplexing Pentagons] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813111016/http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm}}</ref> Rice was born February 16, 1923 in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], and died July 2, 2017 in [[San Diego|San Diego, California]], where she was living with her son and daughter-in-law.\n\n==Geometry==\nMarjorie Rice was a mother of five, who had become an ardent follower of [[Martin Gardner|Martin Gardner\u2019s]] long-running column, \u201cMathematical Games,\u201d which appeared monthly, 1957\u20131986, in the pages of [[Scientific American|Scientific American magazine]]. By the 1970s, Gardner was a popular science writer and amateur mathematician. Rice said later<ref name=\":0\">{{citation|last=Cole|first=K. C.|title=Beating the Pros to the Punch|date=March 11, 1998|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/11/news/mn-27706|journal=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}.</ref> that she would rush to grab each issue from the mail before anyone else could get it, especially her son who subscribed to the magazine.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1975, Rice came across Gardner's articles about [[tessellation]], the mathematics of tiling patterns (determining what kinds of shapes can fit together perfectly without any overlaps or gaps). This is an abstract subject with many scientific applications. In his writings, Gardner claimed that \"only certain types of pentagons could perfectly tile a plane or flat surface, and that all of them were known\u2014or so the mathematicians thought.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Tilings discoveries ===\nDespite having only a high-school education, Rice began devoting her free time to discovering new [[Pentagonal tiling#Monohedral convex pentagonal tilings|pentagonal tiling]]s, ways to tile a [[Plane (geometry)|plane]] (a flat two-dimensional surface) using [[pentagon]]s (a five-sided shape). She worked on the problem in her free time and through the 1975 holiday season \"by drawing diagrams on the kitchen table when no one was around and hiding them when her husband and children came home, or when friends stopped by.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> She even developed her own system of [[Mathematical notation|notation]] to represent the constraints on and relationships between the sides and angles of the pentagons.\n\nIn February 1976, she mailed her discoveries to Gardner using her own home-made notation. He, in turn, sent Rice\u2019s work to [[Doris Schattschneider]], an expert in tiling patterns, who was skeptical at first, saying that Rice\u2019s peculiar notation system seemed odd, like \u201chieroglyphics.\u201d But with careful examination, she was able to validate Rice's results.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBy October 1976, Rice had discovered 58 pentagon tilings (most of them previously unknown), which she arranged into 12 classes. By 1977, she had discovered four new types of tessellating pentagons and over 60 distinct tessellations using pentagons.<ref name=\"Doris\" />\n\nIn the following decade, she discovered several more tiling patterns and three more types of pentagons, thus making major contributions to the field of mathematics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ [[Pentagonal tiling#Monohedral convex pentagonal tilings|Representative tilings]] of the four tiling pentagons discovered by Marjorie Rice \n!Type 9\n!Type 11\n!Type 12\n!Type 13\n|- align=center\n|[[File:P5-type9-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type11 chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type12-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|[[File:P5-type13-chiral_coloring.png|120px]]\n|- align=center\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type9.png|120px]]<BR>b = c = d = e<BR>2A + C = D + 2E = 360\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type11.png|120px]]<BR>2a + c = d = e<BR>A = 90\u00b0, 2B + C = 360\u00b0<BR>C + E = 180\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type12.png|120px]]<BR>2a = d = c + e<BR>A = 90\u00b0, 2B + C = 360\u00b0<BR>C + E = 180\u00b0\n|[[File:Prototile p5-type13.png|120px]]<BR>d = 2a = 2e<BR>B = E = 90\u00b0, 2A + D = 360\u00b0\n|}\n\n=== Accolades ===\nDoris Schattschneider, who helped Martin Gardner popularize the [[pentagon tiling]] discoveries of Rice,<ref name=\":0\" /> lauded her work as an exciting discovery by an amateur mathematician.<ref>[[Doris Schattschneider]]. \"In praise of amateurs.\" In [[David A. Klarner]], editor, ''The Mathematical Gardner'', pages 140\u2013166. Prindle, Weber & Schmidt, Boston, 1981</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813111016/http://britton.disted.camosun.bc.ca/jbperplex.htm|title=Perplexing Pentagons|date=2016-08-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, at a regional meeting of the Mathematical Association of America held in [[Los Angeles]], Schattschneider convinced Rice and her husband to attend the presentation of Rice\u2019s work in a lecture. Before concluding her talk, Schattschneider introduced the amateur mathematician who had advanced the study of tessellation. \u201cAnd everybody in the room . . . gave her a standing ovation.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n* One of the tilings discovered by Rice was cut into glazed ceramic tiles, and installed in the foyer of the headquarters of the [[Mathematical Association of America]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conquermaths.com/news/post/index/264/Marjorie-Rice-The-Most-Remarkable-Housewife-You-ve-Never-Heard-Of|title=Marjorie Rice - The Most Remarkable Housewife You've Never Heard Of|access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Her papers and materials in support of her mathematical discoveries are preserved at the Eug\u00e8ne Strens Recreational Mathematics Collection at the [[University of Calgary]] Library, [[Alberta|Alberta, Canada]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/17513472.2017.1399680|title=Marjorie Rice (16 February 1923\u20132 July 2017)|access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of amateur mathematicians]]\n*[[List of Martin Gardner Mathematical Games columns]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://sites.google.com/site/intriguingtessellations/home Marjorie Rice's home page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070820095233/http://tessellations.home.comcast.net/}}\n*[http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/PentagonTilings/ Pentagon Tilings demonstration]\n*Doris Schattschneider. \"In praise of amateurs.\" In David A. Klarner, editor, ''The Mathematical Gardner'', pages 140\u2013166. Prindle, Weber & Schmidt, Boston, 1981\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Marjorie}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century 